From: Esod <psvita-port>
Subject: [PATCH] hw_cache: do not follow out-of-range patch columns

`HWR_DrawPatchInCache()` walks a patch's column offsets and dereferences them
without ever checking that the column index is inside the patch:

```c
for (block += col*bpp; ncols--; block += bpp, xfrac += xfracstep)
{
	patchcol = (const column_t *)((const UINT8 *)realpatch
	 + LONG(realpatch->columnofs[xfrac>>FRACBITS]));   /* <-- */
```

`columnofs[]` only has `SHORT(realpatch->width)` entries. `xfrac >> FRACBITS`
is derived from `ptexturewidth / pblockwidth` scaling, so it is *expected* to
stay in range — but nothing enforces it, and nothing validates the patch data
either. Read one entry past the array and you take whatever bytes follow for a
byte offset, add them to `realpatch`, and dereference the result.

The failure mode is nasty: **a data abort inside the texture cache**, with no
error message, on a machine where the zone allocator and the WAD loader both
reported success. The developer goes looking for a renderer bug that isn't
there.

We hit this once on a PS Vita, on the first launch after installing the game —
most plausibly a bad read from the memory card producing an inconsistent patch.
It never reproduced, which is exactly why the guard is worth having: corrupt or
truncated data should cost you a texture, not the process.

This patch:

- returns early if the patch or the destination block is NULL,
- returns early on a non-positive patch width,
- **skips** any column whose index falls outside the patch instead of following
  a made-up offset.

No behaviour change on valid data.
---
 src/hardware/hw_cache.c | 26 ++++++++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 22 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

--- a/src/hardware/hw_cache.c
+++ b/src/hardware/hw_cache.c
@@ -49,9 +49,20 @@ static void HWR_DrawPatchInCache(GLMipmap_t *mipmap,
 	UINT8 *block = mipmap->grInfo.data;
 	UINT8 texel;
 	UINT16 texelu16;
+	INT32 patchwidth;
+
+	// Corrupt or truncated patch data must cost a texture, not the process.
+	if (!realpatch || !block)
+		return;
+
+	patchwidth = SHORT(realpatch->width);
+
+	if (patchwidth <= 0)
+		return;

 	x1 = originx;
-	x2 = x1 + SHORT(realpatch->width);
+	x2 = x1 + patchwidth;

 	if (x1 < 0)
 		x = 0;
@@ -92,8 +103,15 @@ static void HWR_DrawPatchInCache(GLMipmap_t *mipmap,
 	for (block += col*bpp; ncols--; block += bpp, xfrac += xfracstep)
 	{
 		INT32 topdelta, prevdelta = -1;
+		INT32 srccol = xfrac>>FRACBITS;
+
+		// columnofs[] only has `patchwidth` entries: reading past it means taking
+		// arbitrary bytes for an offset and following them anywhere.
+		if (srccol < 0 || srccol >= patchwidth)
+			continue;
+
 		patchcol = (const column_t *)((const UINT8 *)realpatch
-		 + LONG(realpatch->columnofs[xfrac>>FRACBITS]));
+		 + LONG(realpatch->columnofs[srccol]));
